post_text:
History has been made!

Senator Kamala Harris is "the first Black woman and the first person of Indian descent to be nominated for national office by a major party, and only the fourth woman in U.S. history to be chosen for a presidential ticket" (New York Times, August 11, 2020).

Senator Harris is a lawyer, former Attorney General of California, United States Senator, graduate of Howard University, member of the AKA (Alpha Kappa Alpha historically black Sorority), and now the First Black Woman on a Presidential ticket!

For we not only celebrate Kamala, but our black girls, teens, young ladies and women of color everywhere! This is a great day for all women in the US and abroad!
Congratulations Kamala Harris!

post_text:
Please see the attached link for full details regarding Excell‚Äôs plan for the upcoming school year.

After reviewing the Safe Learning Plan in great detail, Excell Academy has decided to start the 20-21 school year in a full distance learning model starting September 8th. We will continue in a distance learning model until October 14th, when we will evaluate the prevalence of COVID-19 cases in our community and make a decision to shift learning models (hybrid, full in-person, or continue with distance learning) moving forward.

Childcare for essential workers and for families who are experiencing difficulty with distance learning will be available during the distance learning period. However, please note that there are LIMITED SPACING for on site options during distance learning.

Feel free to contact our front office with questions. Office hours are Monday-Thursday 8-3.

http://www.excellacademy.dreamhosters.com/notifications/

If you had a student who was free or reduced lunch qualified during the 2019-2020 school year you can apply for Pandemic EBT which will provide a one time payment of $325 per qualifying child in food benefits. The deadline to apply has been extended.

New P-EBT updates:
Deadline to apply has been extended to July 31, 2020

Benefits are now extended to Pre K students enrolled in public and charter schools.
Additional funds of $100 per child will be allocated for the summer months and will be issued in August.
To apply for benefits and for more information please visit www.mn.p-ebt.org.

post_text:
Today we stand with our community and celebrate Juneteenth!‚ù§Ô∏èüñ§üíö

Juneteenth marks the end of slavery in the United States. It is an unofficial American holiday celebrated by many Black People annually on the 19th of June in the U.S., and an official holiday "in the state of Texas to commemorate Union general Gordon Granger's reading of federal orders in the city of Galveston, Texas, on the 19th of June in 1865, proclaiming that all previously enslaved people in Texas were free." Texas was the last state recorded to have freed the African slaves in the U.S. Juneteenth is also called by many African Americans - Freedom Day, Emancipation Day, Jubilee Day, Cel-Liberation Day, or the Black Fourth of July.

They are offering a one time payment of up to $325 per child ages 5-18 to help while children are at home for the summer. Go to this website to fill out short application . You will receive card with funds within 10 days.

https://mn.p-ebt.org/en/
shared_text:
Minnesota Department of Human Services
June 8 at 8:04 PM ¬∑

Parents ‚Äì who were NOT receiving SNAP or MFIP benefits on March 18, 2020 ‚Äì can now apply for temporary food support for children who receive free or reduced-price school meals. Apply online at mn.p-ebt.org by June 30, 2020.

Eligible families will receive a P-EBT card in the mail within 30 days. Families on SNAP or MFIP on March 18 do not need to apply; benefits were already issued to their EBT cards.

For more information, see https://mn.gov/dhs/p-ebt/.

Tonight: Temporary curfew in effect - June 1, 2020

Mayor Jeffrey Lunde issued a temporary curfew in effect from 10 p.m. until 4 a.m. on Monday evening and Tuesday evening.
During the curfew, no one may travel on Brooklyn Park streets or public places, except for first responders, members of the media, people going back and forth to work, individuals seeking emergency care or fleeing danger and people experiencing homelessness. We will continue to update you on the curfew through facebook, Instagram, twitter, email and/or text message.

We will be continuing the conversation surrounding the horrific situation our community is currently in, regarding the blessed life and very tragic death of Mr. George Floyd.

We encourage you to join us today at 2pm during our Excell Student Talks phone conference; participants may join in by calling (351) 999-4818. Although, most of this session will be geared toward supporting our students, the entire Excell Community is welcome to join in.

Our guest facilitator for these sessions will be Mrs. Tonicia Abdur Salaam, Head of School of Brightwater Montessori, Equity Coach Trainer / Facilitator. We are honored that Tonicia will help us support our staff, students, and families through this side of these challenging times.

Free COVID-19 Testing this Weekend

Any Minnesotan who wants to be tested for COVID-19 is encouraged to get tested this weekend. There is no charge for the testing and you will not be asked for insurance cards or ID. Everyone will be required to social distance and wear a mask at the testing locations.

When: Saturday, May 23 - Monday, May 25

Time: 10 A.M. ‚Äì 5 P.M. daily or until supplies are exhausted

NO Appointment Needed

Testing Locations:

East St Paul - 1530 Maryland Ave E, St Paul, MN 55106

Minneapolis Armory - 1025 Broadway St. NE, Minneapolis, Minnesota 55413.

Moorhead Armory - 1002 15th Ave N, Moorhead, MN 56560

Duluth Armory - 4015 Airpark Blvd, Duluth, MN 55811

Faribault Armory - 3000 W Airport Rd, Faribault, MN 55021

St. James Armory- 521 Armstrong Blvd N, St James, MN 56081

The sites are hosted by the Minnesota Department of Health, Minnesota National Guard, the State Emergency Operations Center, and the Community Resiliency and Recovery Work Group.

Governor Tim Walz
April 30 at 7:23 PM ¬∑

From building out critical hospital capacity to launching a landmark testing strategy, Minnesota has made meaningful progress in preparing for the worst of the COVID-19 pandemic. Minnesotans have made this possible by staying home and holding down the rate of infection.

But now is not the time for sudden movements. There‚Äôs more work to be done. We need to keep this virus at a simmer, not a boil. We must prioritize the safety of Minnesotans while taking cautious, strategic steps toward getting people safely back to work.

Our Stay Home Order has been extended until May 18. While retail businesses can begin offering curbside pickup on Monday, we‚Äôre asking Minnesotans to continue to stay home, practice social distancing, and wear cloth masks as we turn the dial toward reopening society. #StayHomeMN

Excell Academy will be providing meal bundles for our students and community during this time of closure.

Bundles will include a weeks worth of Breakfasts and Lunches for your children. This week will provide 3 meals per child, next week will provide 7 meals for the week per child.

You and/or your child/children will be able to come and pick up a meal bundle for this week beginning today Wednesday March 18th between the hours of 11:30 and 6:00 pm. If you are unable to come today, you may come Thursday between the hours of 8am to 4pm. Distribution will take place at the front of the school.

If you come Thursday please do not come Friday. Meals are limited and we want to be sure we are able to serve everyone in need. Thank you!
‚†Ä
--
Health Services Manager/Director of Food and Nutrition Services‚†Ä
Excell Academy for Higher Learning

***NO SCHOOL TODAY***
Just a reminder that there will be no school starting today, March 16th-April 4th due to COVID-19 state wide school closures, and our regularly scheduled Spring Break.
.
We want to bring attention to Granite City Food & Brewery and their generous attempt to make sure children have food to eat while out of school. If you know of a family with students who may be in need during this time, please share the below information.
#weareexcellacademy #doingwhateverittakes #mncharterschools
shared_text:
Granite City Food & Brewery (Maple Grove)
March 15 at 6:27 PM ¬∑

Dear Friends,

As we all know, spring break is upon us and there have been many closed schools temporarily in an attempt to control the spread of COVID 19 as well. We believe this is the right decision, but also understand that it may present challenges to families in the communities we serve. We'd like to help.

If you are concerned about ensuring your children have lunch, stop by Granite City Food and Brewery. Every kid can receive a free lunch that contains a turkey sandwich, chips, and applesauce. Completely free, no other purchase is necessary. Just ask for a manager and we will be happy to make it happen.

Valid at Granite City Food and Brewery in Maple Grove, Minnesota.

We are all in this together,

- Your Local Management Team
